l always be accidents and tragedies beyond our control, which is why we must stop dividing the world into winners and losers and ensure that there is a fair share of decency and sufficiency to go around.Visionary and provocative, The Good-Enough Life demonstrates how we can work together to cultivate a good-enough life for all instead of tearing ourselves apart in a race to the top of the social pyramid.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbility. 0aConduct of life. 0aSelf-realization. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh  aAbleism.  aAbsurdity.  aAdolf Hitler.  aArbitrariness.  aAttention economy.  aBiomass (ecology).  aBuddhism.  aCanberra.  aCapitalism.  aCentral Asia.  aChengdu.  aCustomer.  aDisability studies.  aDocking station.  aEconomic recovery.  aElitism.  aEqual opportunity.  aFinancial institution.  aFunding.  aGlobal warming.  aGood and evil.  aGreat Famine (Ireland).  aGreatness.  aHinge.  aHuman migration.  aHuman nature.  aHumility.  aHunter-gatherer.  aIllustration.  aImperialism.  aIncome bracket.  aJacques Derrida.  aLaptop.  aLocal community.  aLoneliness.  aMarket (economics).  aMechanization.  aMeritocracy.  aMining.  aMoisture.  aMorality.  aMutual aid (organization theory).  aNetflix.  aNew Society.  aNew Urbanism.  aPali Canon.  aPatriarchy.  aPlay (activity).  aPositional good.  aQuality of life.  aRacism.  aRational choice theory.  aRationality.  aRosa Luxemburg.  aSelf-esteem.  aShenzhen.  aSuburbanization.  aSuperiority (short story).  aSupporter.  aTechnological revolution.  aTechnology.  aTeleology.  aTransport network.  aTree.  aWaste management.  aWealth.  aWorld War II.  aYacht.  aYale University Press.  aZhuangzi (book).08iTitle is part of eBook p